node.text:
This monumental painting represents the changing urban milieu of late 19th-century Paris. The artist Caillebotte strikingly captured a vast, stark modernity, complete with life-size figures strolling in the foreground and wearing the latest fashions.

Take a closer look in the latest episode of our Art Institute Essentials Tour.

node.text:
To Vincent van Gogh, this picture of his bedroom symbolized relaxation and peace. However, to our eyes the canvas seems to teem with nervous energy and turmoil—an effect heightened by the sharply receding perspective.

Take a closer look at "The Bedroom" (1889)—part of our Art Institute Essentials series.

One of the most famous American paintings of all time, this double portrait by Grant Wood debuted at the Art Institute in 1930, winning the artist a $300 prize and instant fame.

Wood intended this Depression-era canvas to be a positive statement about rural American values during a time of disillusionment. Take a closer look at "American Gothic" in this episode of the Art Institute Essentials Tour.

In the paintings of Picasso’s Blue Period (1901-04), the artist restricted himself to a cold, monochromatic blue palette, flattened forms, and emotional, psychological themes of human misery and alienation. This painting reﬂects the then twenty-two-year-old Picasso’s personal struggle and sympathy for the plight of the downtrodden.

On this episode of Art Institute Essentials Tour, take a closer look at "The Old Guitarist," painted by Picasso between late 1903 and early 1904.

node.text:
Chicago landscape architect Franz Lipp created these fantastical studies in 1928 for an open-air theater in Highland Park, Illinois.

Lipp's design shows a vivid scene of the theater in use, framed by a towering ring of clipped hedges that recalls both the hemispherical form of open-air theaters in antiquity and the pillars of Stonehenge. He evoked another traditional model with the plan for the site, which mimics a neoclassical urn filled with flowers.

Although this project was never realized, Lipp brought similarly dramatic and monumental visions to many projects in the Chicago suburbs, from cemeteries to corporate headquarters.

See these works by Franz Lipp on view in Gallery 285.

NOW OPEN—"Fantastic Landscapes: Hokusai and Hiroshige"

In the 19th century, Japanese printmaking saw two concurrent trends: an intensification of color and a rise in the popularity of landscape images. Capitalizing on these two trends were the most successful print designers of their time, Katsushika Hokusai and Utagawa Hiroshige.

This exhibition showcases a spectacular moment of color in Japanese landscapes—one that would have a lasting impact on artists around the world.

Learn more about "Fantastic Landscapes" at the link in our bio.

Today Muslims around the world celebrate Eid al-Adha, a time for gratitude, for sharing food with family and loved ones, and for giving to those in need. The festival marks the end of Haji, a time of annual pilgrimage for those able to travel. Muslims are expected to travel to Mecca once in their lifetimes if they are physically and financially able. Eid commonly begins by sharing in prayer with pilgrims in Mecca.

Prayer carpets, like these examples from the museum's collection, typically include the arch-shaped design of a prayer niche (mihrab), the focal point in the interior of a mosque which indicates the direction of Mecca for prayer.

Eid al-Adha Mubarak to all those celebrating!

This chubby, boyish image of Ganesha seated with the soles of his feet pressed together developed in Indonesia, where he is particularly popular. Originating in India, he gained special importance across southeast Asia and even in China and Japan.

A protecter against evil spirits, Ganesha has been enshrined in temples dedicated solely to him or placed independently in sacred or dangerous locations. The image is carved fully in the round and features a monster mask behind his head and shoulders.

See "God Ganesha, Remover of Obstacles" (9th/10th century) on view in Gallery 142.
